Refer to [CRC-1147|https://support.atlassian.com/browse/CRC-1147].

{quote}
It would seem more reasonable for crucible to default the link to be defined and then it would be a simple click to unlink it if the user didn't want it. In other words, I would expect the majority of users would want the issue linked verses not linked.
{quote}

See the attached sample screen shot.

The 2.0.6 build came with a CSS file
eg. fecru-2.0.6/content/static/kr6iz1/2static/style/concat.style.251ed754fd74f5a27e000024bd01f650.cache.css

containing entries with absolute http:-based URLs eg.
{code}
.search-quick .quicksearchAuthor .icon {
	background: transparent url(http://localhost:6060/avatar/default?s=16) no-repeat scroll 1px -2px;
}
{code}
and
{code}
ul#quick-nav-drop-down li a.quick-search-author {
	background: transparent url(http://localhost:6060/avatar/default?s=16) no-repeat scroll 4px 2px;
}
{code}

There may be additional entries like that (I haven't done an exhaustive search)

Given that we use Fisheye in with SSL to maintain the privacy of our code, when those URL load along with a normal page in https, we get the mixed secure/non-secure message from MSIE.

h4. Affected browsers
- IE8
- FF 39.0

h4. Developer Tools Output
{noformat}
Loading mixed (insecure) display content "http://localhost:51235/icon" on a secure page [Learn More] [file name redacted]
GET 
http://localhost:51235/icon
{noformat}

h4. Workaround
Disable IDE icons from your profile.

# Select your avatar in the top right of the application to reveal drop down options.
# Select "Profile Settings"
# Select the "Display Settings" tab.
# Scroll down to "IDE Connector"
# Select "No" for "Enable IDE icons"
# Select "Close" to close the modal window.

From Robert and James' comments on CRUC-2213:

{quote}
in the admin console let us choose various available pieces of information which we can drag and drop to constitute the summary. That way you click create and your summary is pre formatted and you can choose to edit it.\
{quote}

{quote}
File name and line numbers would be great in the description. Also for the Summary/Title of the Jira issue it would be good to include the defect classification from Crucible (e.g. "Violation of Standards", "Security Vulnerability" etc, as I have defined in my classification scheme in Crucible).
{quote}

From [Robert's comment|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CRUC-2213?focusedCommentId=175358&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels%3Acomment-tabpanel#action_175358] on CRUC-2213:

{quote}
For trusted apps, I'd also like to be able to have a drop down which shows who are the Assignable users are in Jira for a project. If we go through the trouble of adding those folks to a group, then we could use that same group to show a drop down in Crucible on clicking the create link for an issue and allow us to assign it to whom ever we need to, or leave it automatic and do what you suggested above.
{quote}
